The standard .NET approach is to use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package. It wraps the static `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, etc. calls behind an injectable `IFileSystem` interface.

**Steps:**

1. **Install the package:**
   ```
   dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
   ```

2. **Inject `IFileSystem` instead of using statics:**
   ```csharp
   // Before (untestable)
   File.WriteAllText(path, content);
   var text = File.ReadAllText(path);
   if (Directory.Exists(dir)) { ... }

   // After (testable)
   public class MyService
   {
       private readonly IFileSystem _fs;
       public MyService(IFileSystem fs) => _fs = fs;

       public void DoWork()
       {
           _fs.File.WriteAllText(path, content);
           var text = _fs.File.ReadAllText(path);
           if (_fs.Directory.Exists(dir)) { ... }
       }
   }
   ```

3. **Register in DI:**
   ```csharp
   services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
   ```

4. **In tests, use the companion mock package:**
   ```
   dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
   ```
   ```csharp
   var fs = new MockFileSystem();
   fs.AddFile("/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{}"));
   var svc = new MyService(fs);
   ```

This avoids hand-rolling your own interface and gives you a drop-in in-memory file system for tests.
